@page
@model IndexModel
@{
    Layout = "_Layout";
    ViewData["Title"] = "ListPager Razor Library Examples";
}
<div class="col-md-8 ml-4">
    <h3 class="my-4">
        About ListPagerRazorLibrary Examples
    </h3>
    <p>
        ListPager is set of Bootstrap 4 styled View Components and Partial Views, along with associated models and scripting, wrapped in an Asp.Net Core 3.0 Razor Class Library (RCL).
        See the Github Readme for more technical information. This page is about the examples.
    </p>
    <p>
        The examples (menu items above) use an EF Core in-memory database of an eclectic crew of bloggers, in these different scenarios:
        <ul>
            <li>Post - full page</li>
            <li>Get - full page</li>
            <li>Ajax, single Partial View - data list and pager together</li>
            <li>Ajax, separate Partial Views - data list and pager</li>
            <li>Ajax, Client-side rendering - Json for the data list, Partial View or View Component for the pager</li>
        </ul>
    </p>
    <p>
        There are notes with each example. Here are some common things to note:

        <dl>

            <dt class="my-2">Override of ListPager Partial Views</dt>
            <dd class="px-4">
                <div class="mb-2">
                    In all of the examples, ListPager's partial view <code>_ListPagerPageOf</code> is overriden by
                    <code class="ml-4">ListPagerExamples/Pages/Shared/_ListPagerPageOf.cshtml</code>
                    to use class='text-danger'. It effects all examples where the Partial View version
                    of _ListPager is used.
                </div>

                <div>
                    The View Component ListPager is not affected since
                    it's corresponding view component <code>ListPagerPageOf</code> is not overriden.
                </div>
            </dd>
            <dt class="my-2">Override of ListPager View Components</dt>
            <dd class="px-4">
                <div class="mb-2">
                    Where the View Component version of <code>ListPager</code> is used the <code>ListPagerPageSize</code> is overridden by
                    <code>ListPagerExamples/Pages/Shared/Components/ListPagerPageSize.cshtml</code>, to display the Page Size UI with no input.
                </div>
                <div>
                    The <i>Partial View</i> version <code>_ListPagerPageSize</code> is not affected.
                </div>
            </dd>
            <dt class="my-2">Folder Structure</dt>
            <dd class="px-4">
                To override the library's static assets, partial views or view components, the overriding element must reside
                in a folder structure that mirrors the Library's <strong>relative to wwwroot</strong>:
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        css/pager.css
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        js/pager.js - consider forking rather than overriding this.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        Pages/Shared/[_PartialView].cshtml
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        Pages/Components/[ViewComponent].cshtml
                    </li>
                </ul>
                <strong>NB:</strong> Library names are case-sensitive: "Css" is not the same as "css"
            </dd>

            <dt class="my-2">BloggerPageModel</dt>
            <dd class="px-4">
                Each of the Examples' page classes inherit from this class and it handles common data/method needs.
            </dd>
            <dt class="my-2">Request Verification Token</dt>
            <dd class="px-4">
                All of the Ajax examples send the RequestVerificationToken by setting the Http Header with the value of an
                "Html.AntiForgeryToken()" hidden input. You can use a different method if you prefer. I'd not recommend ignoring it.
            </dd>
            <dt class="my-2">Search</dt>
            <dd class="px-4">
                The Search functionality demonstrates how to implement features in concert with ListPager, it is not part of ListPager.
            </dd>
        </dl>
    </p>

</div>
